d medieval sources, including Thucydides, Plato, Paul the Apostle, and Augustine, as well as contemporary discourses of self-transformation, such as the public testimonies of Caitlyn Jenner and Rachel Dolezal, Ellwanger elucidates the role of language in signifying and authenticating identity. Timely and original, Ellwanger’s study formulates a transhistorical theory of personal transformation that will be of interest to scholars working in social theory, philosophy, rhetoric, and the history of Christianity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aRhetoricxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSelf. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aEpistrophe.  aEthos.  aIdentity Politics.  aIdentity.  aMetanoia.  aPersonal Transformation.  aRhetoric.  aRhetorical Theory.  aSubjectivity.  aThe Self.1 aGehrke, Pat J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271086804?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271086804423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271086804/original  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK